<p>
Dear Orange:
<p>
I read some of your deconstruction of Bill W's beliefs, and am a little perplexed.
For starters, by now many millions of people have gotten and stayed sober through
AA. Of those, many never smoked and many quit smoking after being sober for some
months or years. Yes it is certainly true that Bill W and many others struggled with
addictive issues the rest of their lives. Would you have preferred that they die
drunk many years earlier and so avoid that struggle? That's what I'm hearing.
<p>
AA in the 80s recognized as a Fellowship how destructive smoking was and made many
meetings smoke-free; many members after watching their elders die of awful diseases
quit. But don't you feel you're throwing the baby out with the bathwater? If even
one drunk gets to stop for good being a slave to the bottle, isn't that a good
thing?
<p>
I've been sober 15 years, don't smoke, and hardly go to meetings. But I know that AA
saved my life; without it I'd have been dead a long time ago.
<p>
Amy

<p>
<font color="blue">
